list_page_teaser: This gallery contains images of Twin Peaks characters who work at the Great Northern Hotel and the Packard Sawmill.  Click to learn more!
description_html: These spiritual portraits of Twin Peaks characters who work at the Great Northern Hotel and the Packard Sawmill show how different Benjamin Horne and Catherine Martell are from Pete Martell and Josie Packard. Meanwhile, Audrey's personality has the Yellow realism of the first group and the Red amiability of the second.
story_html:
The images make it clear that Benjamin Horne and Catherine Martell have very similar personalities. Both are very logical, pragmatic, and decisive — with Catherine's image showing she is just a little bit colder than Ben.

The portraits also show that Pete Martell's and Josie Packard's personalities are similar to each other — but the polar opposite of Ben's and Catherine's. Josie and Pete are both shy, idealistic, sensitive, and perceptive — with Pete being a bit more outgoing and friendly than Josie, and her being a bit more shy and intuitive.

image_list.title: Audrey Horne
image_list.subtitle_html: High School Student and Ben Horne's Daughter
image_list.gallery_page_teaser: Audrey Horne's spiritual portrait shows she is open-minded and friendly.  Click on the image to learn more!
image_list.explain_dom: The Yellow in this spiritual portrait represents Audrey's dominant personality trait, her realistic outlook.  In Extraverts, the dominant trait is directed outwardly, and spiritual portraits use a long vertical line to represent this, because it is the side of their personality that is most evident.
image_list.explain_aux: The Red in this spiritual portrait represents Audrey's auxiliary personality trait, her friendliness and amiability.  In Extraverts, the auxiliary trait is directed inwardly, and spiritual portraits use a horizontal line to represent this.

image_list.title: Pete Martell
image_list.subtitle_html: Retired Lumberjack and Fisherman
image_list.gallery_page_teaser: Pete Martell's spiritual portrait shows he is very open to new ideas and experiences, and very amiable but not necessarily outgoing.  Click on the image to learn more!
image_list.explain_dom: The Red in this spiritual portrait represents Pete's dominant personality trait, his fairly strong preference for emotion over logic.  In Introverts, the dominant trait is directed inwardly, and spiritual portraits use a long horizontal line to represent this.
image_list.explain_aux: The Blue in this spiritual portrait represents Pete's auxiliary personality trait, his openness to new ideas.  In Introverts, the auxiliary trait is directed outwardly, and spiritual portraits use a vertical line to represent this, because it is more evident than the dominant function.
